5|$|Covered {{interest}} rate parity is a no-arbitrage condition in foreign exchange markets which {{depends on the}} availability of the forward market. It can be rearranged to give the forward <b>exchange</b> <b>rate</b> {{as a function of the}} other variables. The forward <b>exchange</b> <b>rate</b> depends on three known variables: the spot <b>exchange</b> <b>rate,</b> the domestic {{interest rate}}, and the foreign interest rate. This effectively means that the forward rate is the price of a forward contract, which derives its value from the pricing of spot contracts and the addition of information on available interest rates.|$|E
